When we're thinking about the big questions, he reminds us, let's be aware of our all-too-human brains.", "event": "TED2011", "language": "en", "language_swap": false, "name": "Dan Ariely: Beware conflicts of interest", "slug": "dan_ariely_beware_conflicts_of_interest", "series_slug": null, "speakers": [{"id": "332", "slug": "dan_ariely", "is_published": true, "firstname": "Dan", "lastname": "Ariely", "middleinitial": "", "title": "", "description": "Behavioral economist", "photo_url": "https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/1a36ab42198d58992285a8570a4fb7e75e21d10e_254x191.jpg", "whatotherssay": "If you want to know why you always buy a bigger television than you intended, or why you think it's perfectly fine to spend a few dollars on a cup of coffee at Starbucks, or why people feel better after taking a 50-cent aspirin but continue to complain of a throbbing skull when they're told the pill they took just cost one penny, Ariely has the answer.", "whotheyare": "The dismal science of economics is not as firmly grounded in actual behavior as was once supposed. In \"Predictably Irrational,\" Dan Ariely told us why.", "whylisten": "

Dan Ariely is a professor of psychology and behavioral economics at Duke University and a founding member of the Center for Advanced Hindsight. He is the author of the bestsellers Predictably Irrational, The Upside of Irrationality, and The Honest Truth About Dishonesty -- as well as the TED Book Payoff: The Hidden Logic that Shapes Our Motivations.

Through his research and his (often amusing and unorthodox) experiments, he questions the forces that influence human behavior and the irrational ways in which we often all behave.

Dan Ariely is a professor of psychology and behavioral economics at Duke University and a founding member of the Center for Advanced Hindsight. He is the author of the bestsellers Predictably Irrational, The Upside of Irrationality, and The Honest Truth About Dishonesty -- as well as the TED Book Payoff: The Hidden Logic that Shapes Our Motivations.
